# 📊 Correlation vs Causation — Interactive Teaching Tool

An interactive Streamlit app for teaching the distinction between correlation and causation in university social science courses. Designed for both student self-exploration and live classroom demonstration.

## ✨ Features

- **🎛️ Confounder Simulator** — Students drag sliders to control a hidden confounding variable (summer heat) and watch unrelated variables (ice cream sales, drownings) become spuriously correlated. A reveal toggle colors points by the confounder for the "aha" moment.
- **🌍 Real Examples** — Three preloaded scenarios (firefighters/fire damage, shoe size/reading ability, chocolate/Nobel laureates) with a reveal-the-confounder toggle.
- **🧠 Your Turn** — Guided reasoning practice walking through the four possibilities (A→B, B→A, confounder, coincidence) for classic scenarios, with discussion notes on reveal.

## 🚀 Quick Start (Local)

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/correlation-vs-causation.git
cd correlation-vs-causation
pip install -r requirements.txt
streamlit run app.py
```

The app will open at `http://localhost:8501`.

## ☁️ Deploy to Streamlit Community Cloud (Free)

1. Push this repo to your GitHub account.
2. Go to [share.streamlit.io](https://share.streamlit.io) and sign in with GitHub.
3. Click **"New app"**, select this repo, branch `main`, main file `app.py`.
4. Click **Deploy**. You'll get a public URL like `https://your-app.streamlit.app`.
5. Share that URL with students — no installation required on their end.

Updates pushed to GitHub redeploy automatically.

## 🏫 Classroom Use

**Lecture demo (15–20 min):**
1. Open Tab 1. With sliders at default, point out the apparent correlation between ice cream and drowning.
2. Ask students to predict what will happen when you set "heat drives ice cream" to 0. Run it.
3. Restore sliders. Toggle "Reveal the confounder." Let the color gradient do the teaching.
4. Switch to Tab 2. Walk through one real example — don't reveal the confounder until students propose one.

**Student homework:**
- Tab 3 makes a good individual or small-group assignment. Ask students to submit their four-possibility analysis for one scenario.

